{
${\footnote $ Introduction}
{\b \fs24 Introduction}\plain\par\par
#{\footnote # loc1}
K{\footnote K Introduction}
\pard \plain \qj \fs20 \f0 Thank you for trying out SABRE Fighter Plane Simulator, 
an on-going game project for Linux and Windows NT/95 developed under 
the {\uldb GNU Public License}{\v loc23} as a labor 
of love by flight-simulation enthusiasts.
\par
\par
{\b Quick Tips}
\par
If you've just downloaded and run SABRE, you are currently in {\uldb Demo Mode}{\v loc21}. 
It is March, 1953, and in the frigid skies over Korea, American F-86 SabreJets, F-84 
ThunderJets and F-51 Mustangs are engaged with North Korean MiG-15s and Yak-9s 
in a whirling "furball". From positions on the ground 37-mm AAA fire adds to the 
danger. The demo switches viewpoint from plane to plane, giving you a 
"God's-Eye" view of the action. 
\par
\par
To fly yourself, choose a selection from the 
{\uldb Flights}{\v loc22} menu. When you start a flight, the mouse pointer will 
dissapear. Your mouse is now functioning as the "stick", and by moving it left,
right, forwards or backwards you make the plane bank left, bank right, nose down 
or nose up. The stick position is indicated by a green circle which moves around 
near center of the screen. See {\uldb HUD Diagram}{\v loc51}. 
\par
\par
Clicking on the RIGHT mouse button will PAUSE the game, and return the mouse pointer 
to allow you to select a menu item. If your guns are armed (as indicated by the presence 
of the gun pipper, a green circle with a dot), clicking on the LEFT mouse button will 
fire them.
\par
\par
You can exit the game at any time by hitting {\b\f1 Q} or {\b\f1 q} or {\b\f1<ESC>},
or by selecting {\bExit} from the {\uldb Flights}{\v loc22} menu. 
\par
\par
Send inquiries and bug reports to {\b dan@cobite.com}.
\par
\par
Check out the SABRE Web Site:
\par
{ \b sabre.cobite.com }
\par
for latest patches and documentation
\par
\par
\pard
