{
${\footnote $ Autopilot}
K{\footnote K Autopilot}
{\b \fs24 Autopilot}\plain\par\par
#{\footnote # loc24}
\pard \plain \qj \fs20 \f0 
Choosing {\b Autopilot} from the {\b Controls} Menu, or pressing {\b \f1 A} engages 
or disengages the Autopilot. In SABRE, the Autopilot does a lot more than usual. You 
can think of him or her has your copilot, ready to take over at any time if you get 
weary of battle. When you invoke the Autopilot, the same logic used for the computer-
controlled planes will now govern your plane (for better or worse). 
} {\plain \page}


{
K{\footnote K Flights}
${\footnote $ Flights}
{\b \fs24 Flights}\plain\par\par
#{\footnote # loc22}
\pard \plain \qj \fs20 \f0
\par
The following missions are available from the {\b Flights} Menu: 
\par
\par
{\b Just Fly}
\par
Just fly around. No one will bother you! And if you feel like taking a shot at 
something, go ahead ... maybe it will blow up!
\par
\par
{\b Takeoff}
\par
Takeoff from the runway. Use the {\b *} for full throttle, {\b W} to release 
your wheel brakes. When your airspeed reaches 160 kts, pull back gently and 
rise!
\par
\par
{\b Shoot1}
\par
Puts you on the six of a rather clueless MiG-15. Get the pipper (see {\uldb HUD Diagram}{\v loc51}) 
on the Lead Box and pull the trigger!
\par
\par
{\b Shoot2}
\par
Same setup as Shoot1 above, except now the MiG will break to your left.
\par
\par
{\b Shoot3}
\par
Same setup again, except now the MiG will "jink" back and forth
\par
\par
{\b Dogfight}
\par
This is it, buddy! Your're one-on-one against a hot MiG-15 pilot, who wants you to
die for your country. The setup is random, he might be in front of you, or behind you. 
Use the {\uldb Target Track}{\v loc61} view to quickly find out where he is.
\par
\par
{\b Melee}
\par
You're part of a 5-plane formation of SabreJets heading straight into MiG Alley. You'll 
hear your wingman engage a flight of MiGs up ahead. Use the {\uldb Target Track II}{\v loc62} 
view, along with the {\b <ENTER>} key, to pick out a target in the fray. You'll need to 
cycle through your wingmen before getting to the MiGs, which (if you don't know) are the 
planes with the big red stars on them. Then use {\uldb Target Track}{\v loc61} 
to steer your way to him. Do your part to help your buddies see this one through!
\par
\par
{\b Furball}
\par
Holey Smokes! What a mess ... we've got SabreJets, ThunderJets, Mustangs, MiGs and Yaks all 
over the place! Again, use that {\uldb Target Track II}{\v loc62} and the {\uldb Target Track}{\v loc61} 
views to locate and head towards an enemy plane. Check your six!
\par
\par
{\b Mig Jump}
\par
And now, for the other point of view. You are patrolling in your MiG-15, with your 
loyal Wing Comrade, Commander Jing, when you  
spot a flight of three F-51 Mustangs below you. Use "zoom and boom" tactics to defeat 
the less powerful American planes. 
\par
\par
{\b Yak Attack!}
\par
See how your F-51 Mustang, the greatest American piston-engine fighter ever made, 
measures up against the Russian Yak-09, also of World War II vintage.
}
\par
\par 
{\b ThunderJets}
\par
The F84 ThunderJet is a fine plane, but the MiG-15 outclasses it in nearly every 
respect. You and your two wingmen will need to use your superior skill and training 
to defeat a flight of MiGs heading your way!      
\par
\par
{\b NEW! Ground Attack I-III}
\par 
New with Version 0.2.3, three intense ground attack missions pitting you, armed 
with HVAR rockets and M43 500lb bombs, against rather excitable ground units who 
will send 60mm AAA fire your way. See {\uldb Air-To-Ground Missions }{\v loc100} 
for some pointers. 
\par
\par

{\plain \page}

{
${\footnote $ Air-To-Ground Missions }
K{\footnote K Air-To-Ground Missions }
#{\footnote # loc100}
{\b \fs24 Air-To-Ground Missions}\par\par
 \pard \plain \f1 \fs10
The "Ground Attack" scenarios introduce air-to-ground ordinance into SABRE. 
Armed with HVAR high-velocity rockets, M43 500lb bombs, and 
M64 1000lb bombs, you will attack ground units who, not  
surprisingly, will retaliate with deadly 60mm anti-aircraft fire. 
Also, a few MiGs may drop by to say hello. 
\par
\par
Air-to-ground ordinance is also available in the "fly" mission, 
and you may want to develop your bombing and strafing skills by attacking 
the red pyramids at "Target Range Omega", without fear of 
retaliation. In the "gru" missions, the red pyramids will be 
replaced by the ground units. 
\par
\par
To select your air-to-ground ordinance, use the 'N' key. The 
type of ordinance selected will appear in the lower left of 
your hud ... "HVAR" for rockets, "M43" for 500lb bombs, and 
"M64" for 1000lb bombs. 
\par
\par 
All of the missions have you pointed towards a dark circular 
area, "Target Range Omega", where you will find the ground units 
(but not quite before they notice you!). The ground units consist 
of a column of trucks and AAA vehicles. The AAA vehicles, for now, 
use the same shape data as the trucks, so they, well, they look 
like trucks. But they dont quack like a truck, nor walk like a 
truck, so believe me, they aint trucks!  
\par
\par
If you get turned around and confused, your 
"waypoint indicators", horizontal and vertical green lines, 
can help you get back on track. 
In Ground Attack II & III, you are also being tracked by MiGs. To select 
them for targeting, press the <ENTER> key, however, the waypoint 
indicators will no longer guide you to the ground targets. 
In II, you should have plenty of time to make a few passes 
before having to deal with the MiG, in III, well, you'll see ... 
\par 
\par
Aiming 
\par 
------ 
\par
Aiming your air-to-ground ordinance is purely a matter of  
feel. The sight is fixed on the center of your hud for both 
rockets and bombs, no computed "cueing" is given. Bombs are 
particularly difficult to aim accurately. You'll have to drop 
a few at a consistent dive angle and speed to get a sense of 
where you want the target to be on release. I wish I could 
give you some better advice, but, hey, I haven't figured out 
how to drop the darn things on target yet either! 
\par 
\par
Rockets are a little easier to aim, plus they look kind of 
neat. You also get to see where they hit, which brings up 
another issue ... 
\par
\par
Bomb Damage Assesment 
\par
---------------------
\par
The other thing about the bombs is desiring to see if, 
after dodging through MiGs and flak at great risk, you 
managed to hit anything. However, doing so often involves 
floundering around and making yourself a sitting duck for 
AAA fire, or stalling, or just plowing into the ground. 
\par
\par 
This issue will be resolved in the next update by providing 
a "weapon viewpoint" so you can, ala Dr. StrangeLove, 
ride your bomb right into the ground! Meanwhile, try a steep 
climb after release and using the back view ('4' key) to eyeball 
the results. 
\par
\par
Hints
\par 
----- 
\par
The ground units are moving in columns perpendicular to you. 
To get the most out of your ordinance, you want to swing around 
and approach them head on. 
\par
\par
Stay high and fast. Release your weapons no lower than 4000 feet 
AGL and quickly pull away. If you get low and slow over those 
60s, you are one dead pilot. 
\par
\par
In "Ground Attack I", you will be flying an F-84 ThunderJet, which did most 
of the ground attack work in the later stages of the Korean War. 
Be careful not to stall this birdy ... I've added a spin factor 
to it's flight model which makes stalling particularly dangerous .
\par
} {\plain \page}

{
${\footnote $ Demo Mode}
K{\footnote K Demo Mode}
#{\footnote # loc21}
{\b \fs24 Demo Mode}\par\par
\plain \qj \fs20 \f0 In Demo Mode, you have a "God's-Eye" view of the battle. 
The simulation automatically switches the view-point from plane to plane, 
attempting to show you the most interesting events occurring. 
Demo Mode is a good way to observe how the computer-controlled 
pilots maneuver and shoot (not particularly well, as of now.) 
If you get excited enough to join in, hit {\b\f1 A} or select 
{\uldb Autopilot}{\v loc24} 
from the Controls Menu at any point, 
and you will be put in control of the selected aircraft.
} {\plain \page}


{
${\footnote $ Window Size}
K{\footnote K Window Size}
#{\footnote # loc30}
{\b \fs24 Changing the Window Size}\par\par
\plain \qj \fs20 \f0 
\par
You can change the size of the window you are running SABRE 
in by simply dragging on the bottom right corner, as you would 
any other window. The one caveat is that the larger you make the 
window, the slower the game will run, as more pixels have to be generated. 
Additionally, the cockpit graphic will only appear when the window is 
320x200 pixels. 
} {\plain \page}

